                    <div class="section" id="case_story">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>INCLUSION IN ACTION: A TALE OF TWO TEAMS</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>CASE STORY: THE MONDAY MORNING MEETING</h4><div><p>Read both scenarios below carefully. They follow the same team in the same workplace - but with two very different leadership approaches.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>As you read, pay attention to:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>How each leader's behaviour affects the team</li><li>The impact on trust, morale, and contribution</li><li>What feels familiar from your own experience</li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="background: #dcfce7; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin: 20px 0; border-left: 5px solid #4ade80;"><h4 style="color: #166534; margin-bottom: 15px;">SCENARIO A: INCLUSIVE LEADERSHIP IN ACTION</h4><p style="font-style: italic; color: #166534; margin-bottom: 20px;">Setting: Monday morning team meeting at a retail distribution centre. The team includes warehouse operatives, admin staff, and team leaders.</p><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><p><b>The Scene:</b></p><p style="margin-top: 10px;">Team Leader <b>Rachel</b> opens the weekly meeting. Before diving into operations, she takes a moment to check in with the team.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px; padding-left: 20px; border-left: 3px solid #4ade80;"><i>"Before we start, I wanted to acknowledge that Amir suggested last week that we change the shift handover process. We have trialled it this week and the feedback has been really positive. Thanks Amir - that is exactly the kind of input that makes us better."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Amir, who joined the team six months ago and is often quiet in meetings, looks surprised but pleased. A few colleagues nod in agreement.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Rachel continues: <i>"I also know some of you have been finding the new system challenging. No judgement - it is a big change. Maya, I know you mentioned you learn better with written guides. I have created a step-by-step document that might help. Anyone else who would find that useful, just let me know."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Maya, who is dyslexic and sometimes struggles with verbal-only instructions, smiles gratefully.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">As the meeting progresses, Rachel notices that <b>Dev</b>, one of the newer team members, has not spoken. Rather than putting him on the spot, she says: <i>"Dev, I would value your perspective on this when you are ready - no pressure to speak now, but I would like to hear your thoughts later if you prefer."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">After the meeting, Dev approaches Rachel privately and shares an observation about a safety concern he had noticed. Rachel thanks him and acts on it immediately.</p></div><div style="background: #f0fdf4; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;"><p><b>The Impact:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li><b>Trust:</b> Team members feel safe to contribute ideas and raise concerns, knowing they will be heard and credited</li><li><b>Morale:</b> People feel valued as individuals, not just as workers filling a role</li><li><b>Team Contribution:</b> The team benefits from diverse perspectives - Amir's process improvement, Dev's safety observation, and Maya's learning needs being accommodated</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="background: #fee2e2; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin: 20px 0; border-left: 5px solid #f87171;"><h4 style="color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 15px;">SCENARIO B: EXCLUSIONARY LEADERSHIP IN ACTION</h4><p style="font-style: italic; color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 20px;">Same setting, same team - but a different leader.</p><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><p><b>The Scene:</b></p><p style="margin-top: 10px;">Team Leader <b>Mark</b> opens the Monday meeting abruptly.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px; padding-left: 20px; border-left: 3px solid #f87171;"><i>"Right, let us get through this quickly. Targets are down and I need everyone to step up. I do not want to hear excuses."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Last week, <b>Amir</b> had emailed Mark with a suggestion about improving the shift handover process. Mark never responded. In the meeting, Mark announces a new handover procedure - almost identical to Amir's suggestion - but presents it as his own idea. Amir says nothing, but his expression hardens.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">When discussing the new system, Mark turns to <b>Maya</b>: <i>"Maya, you have been making mistakes on the system. Everyone else has got it by now. You need to pay more attention."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Maya's face reddens. She had asked for written instructions twice but was told to "just listen carefully like everyone else." She does not mention her dyslexia - she has learned it is not safe to.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Mark notices <b>Dev</b> is quiet and says loudly: <i>"Dev, you have been here a month now. If you do not have anything to contribute, maybe you need to think about whether this team is right for you."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Dev, who had noticed a safety concern earlier in the week, decides not to mention it. <i>"What is the point?"</i> he thinks. <i>"He will just dismiss it or blame me for not fixing it myself."</i></p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">After the meeting, several team members gather by the coffee machine, venting frustration. Two of them are already looking at job listings on their phones.</p></div><div style="background: #fef2f2; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px;"><p><b>The Impact:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li><b>Trust:</b> Team members do not trust Mark to listen, credit their ideas, or support them - so they stop trying</li><li><b>Morale:</b> People feel undervalued, publicly criticised, and unsupported - leading to disengagement and job searching</li><li><b>Team Contribution:</b> Good ideas go unshared, safety concerns go unreported, and the team loses the benefit of diverse perspectives and experiences</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>KEY CONTRASTS</h4><div><table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 10px;"><tr style="background: #f8f9fa;"><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left; border-bottom: 2px solid #e0e0e0;">Aspect</th><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left; border-bottom: 2px solid #e0e0e0; color: #166534;">Rachel (Inclusive)</th><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left; border-bottom: 2px solid #e0e0e0; color: #991b1b;">Mark (Exclusionary)</th></tr><tr><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><b>Recognition</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Credits team members publicly for their contributions</td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Takes credit for others' ideas without acknowledgement</td></tr><tr><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><b>Individual Needs</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Proactively accommodates different learning styles</td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Expects everyone to adapt to one approach</td></tr><tr><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><b>Participation</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Creates safe space for quieter voices without pressure</td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Publicly calls out quiet team members</td></tr><tr><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><b>Feedback Culture</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Makes it safe to share concerns privately</td><td style="padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;">Creates fear that shuts down communication</td></tr><tr><td style="padding: 12px;"><b>Result</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; color: #166534;"><b>Team members contribute, innovate, and stay</b></td><td style="padding: 12px; color: #991b1b;"><b>Team members disengage, withhold, and leave</b></td></tr></table></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="feedback-box-render"><h4>Reflection: Where Have I Seen Something Similar?</h4><p>Think about your own workplace experiences - as a team member, team leader, or observer.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Have you witnessed or experienced situations similar to either scenario?</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>A time when someone's contribution was publicly recognised (or ignored)?</li><li>A moment when individual needs were accommodated (or dismissed)?</li><li>A situation where someone felt safe to speak up (or stayed silent out of fear)?</li></ul><textarea placeholder="Write your reflection here...

Think about a specific situation you have witnessed or experienced. What happened? How did it affect the people involved?"></textarea></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="feedback-box-render"><h4>Reflection: How Does This Relate to My Own Team?</h4><p>Now think about your current role and the team you lead or work within.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Consider these questions:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Which of Rachel's inclusive behaviours do you already practise?</li><li>Are there any behaviours from Mark's approach that you recognise in yourself or others?</li><li>What is one small change you could make to be more inclusive in your next team interaction?</li></ul><textarea placeholder="Write your reflection here...

Be honest with yourself - we all have room to grow. What inclusive behaviour could you strengthen or adopt?"></textarea></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Key Takeaway:</b></p><p>Inclusion is not about grand gestures or policies - it is about the everyday moments. How you run a meeting, respond to an idea, accommodate a need, or invite someone to contribute. These small actions, repeated consistently, create either a culture of inclusion or a culture of exclusion.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">As you continue through this module, keep Rachel and Mark in mind. The difference between them is not personality - it is behaviour. And behaviour can be learned, practised, and improved.</p></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="section" id="unconscious_bias">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>UNDERSTANDING UNCONSCIOUS BIAS AT WORK</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>WHAT IS UNCONSCIOUS BIAS?</h4><div><p><b>Unconscious bias</b> refers to the automatic mental shortcuts our brains make when processing information about people and situations.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;">These biases are:</p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li><b>Automatic:</b> They happen quickly, without conscious thought or intention</li><li><b>Often unintentional:</b> We are usually unaware they are influencing our decisions</li><li><b>Shaped by experience:</b> They develop from our upbringing, culture, media exposure, and past experiences</li><li><b>Universal:</b> Everyone has unconscious biases - they are a normal part of how our brains work</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Think of your brain as having two systems: a fast, automatic system that makes quick judgements (where bias lives), and a slower, more deliberate system that analyses and reasons. Most of our daily decisions use the fast system - which is efficient but prone to bias.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Why does understanding bias matter for leaders?</b></p><p>As a team leader, you make decisions every day that affect your team members - from who gets opportunities and recognition, to how you give feedback, to whose ideas you pay attention to. Unconscious bias can quietly influence all of these decisions, often in ways that disadvantage certain people.</p><p>The good news is that once you become aware of your biases, you can take steps to counteract them and make fairer, more intentional decisions.</p></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>COMMON WORKPLACE BIASES</h4><div><p>Here are five types of unconscious bias that commonly affect workplace decisions:</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="interactive-activity-wrapper"><div class="accordion-container"><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">1. Affinity Bias</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What it is:</b> The tendency to warm to people who are similar to us - whether that is shared background, interests, experiences, or characteristics.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>How it shows up at work:</b></p><ul><li>Hiring people who remind us of ourselves</li><li>Giving more time and opportunities to team members we "click" with</li><li>Building closer relationships with people from similar backgrounds</li><li>Favouring candidates who went to the same university or have similar hobbies</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>The impact:</b> Teams become less diverse, and people who are different from the leader may miss out on opportunities, mentoring, and recognition.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">2. Confirmation Bias</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What it is:</b> The tendency to seek out, interpret, and remember information that confirms what we already believe, while dismissing information that contradicts our views.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>How it shows up at work:</b></p><ul><li>Forming an early impression of someone and then only noticing things that confirm it</li><li>Giving more weight to feedback that supports our existing view of a team member</li><li>Dismissing ideas from people we have already judged as "not very capable"</li><li>Remembering a person's mistakes more than their successes (or vice versa)</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>The impact:</b> People get "stuck" with reputations that may not reflect their true abilities. Good ideas get ignored because of who suggested them.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">3. Gender Bias</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What it is:</b> Unconscious assumptions about what men and women are like, what they are good at, and how they should behave.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>How it shows up at work:</b></p><ul><li>Assuming women are better at nurturing or administrative tasks</li><li>Expecting men to be more assertive or technically skilled</li><li>Judging the same behaviour differently based on gender (e.g., describing assertive women as "aggressive")</li><li>Overlooking women for leadership roles or men for flexible working arrangements</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>The impact:</b> Career progression and opportunities become limited by gender rather than ability. Talented people are held back by stereotypes.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">4. Age Bias</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What it is:</b> Assumptions about people based on their age - whether younger or older.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>How it shows up at work:</b></p><ul><li>Assuming younger workers are not experienced enough for responsibility</li><li>Assuming older workers are resistant to change or technology</li><li>Overlooking older candidates for roles or training opportunities</li><li>Not taking younger team members' ideas seriously</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>The impact:</b> People are judged by their age rather than their actual skills and potential. The organisation misses out on the benefits of multi-generational teams.</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">5. Halo Effect</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What it is:</b> The tendency to let one positive trait or achievement influence our overall perception of a person, overlooking their weaknesses or areas for development.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>How it shows up at work:</b></p><ul><li>Assuming a top performer is good at everything</li><li>Overlooking poor behaviour from someone who delivers results</li><li>Promoting someone based on one standout achievement rather than overall capability</li><li>Giving more favourable performance reviews to people we like personally</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>The impact:</b> People are promoted or rewarded based on an incomplete picture. Development needs are overlooked. Standards are applied inconsistently.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>HOW BIAS CAN AFFECT WORKPLACE DECISIONS</h4><div><p>Unconscious bias can influence almost any decision you make as a leader. Here are some common areas where bias creeps in:</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Recruitment and Selection:</b></p><ul><li>Whose CV gets shortlisted based on name, age, or education</li><li>Who performs "well" in interviews (people similar to the interviewer often seem more competent)</li><li>Who is seen as a "culture fit" (often means "like us")</li></ul><p><b>Performance Management:</b></p><ul><li>Who gets noticed for good work</li><li>Whose mistakes are remembered vs. overlooked</li><li>How feedback is given and how harshly poor performance is judged</li></ul><p><b>Opportunities and Development:</b></p><ul><li>Who gets stretch assignments and high-visibility projects</li><li>Who is mentored and sponsored for promotion</li><li>Who is encouraged to apply for new roles</li></ul><p><b>Day-to-Day Leadership:</b></p><ul><li>Whose ideas get taken seriously in meetings</li><li>Who gets interrupted and who gets listened to</li><li>Who is included in informal networks and conversations</li></ul></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>Key takeaway:</b></p><p>Bias is not about being a "bad person" - it is a normal part of how our brains work. The challenge for leaders is to become aware of these tendencies and put systems in place to counteract them. In the next section, you will test your awareness of bias in workplace scenarios.</p></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="section" id="bias_quiz">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>BIAS IN ACTION: WORKPLACE SCENARIOS</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>TEST YOUR BIAS AWARENESS</h4><div><p>Read each workplace scenario carefully and decide whether bias is present. After you answer, you will receive feedback explaining:</p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>What type of bias is involved (if any)</li><li>Why it matters</li><li>One inclusive leadership action that could counter it</li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="interactive-activity-wrapper" id="workplace-bias-quiz"><div class="bias-scenario" style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">Scenario 1</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;">Sarah is reviewing CVs for a customer service role. She notices that one candidate, James, went to the same university as her and played rugby - just like she did. She finds herself thinking "He would be a great fit for the team" before she has even finished reading his application.</p><p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px;">Is bias present in this scenario?</p><div class="scenario-options" style="display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'yes', 1)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">Yes, bias is present</button><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'no', 1)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">No bias present</button></div><div class="scenario-feedback" id="feedback-1" style="display: none; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px;"><p><b>Type of Bias:</b> Affinity Bias</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Why it matters:</b> Sarah is forming a positive opinion of James based on shared experiences rather than his qualifications for the role. This could lead her to overlook more qualified candidates who do not share her background, reducing diversity and potentially missing the best person for the job.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Inclusive Leadership Action:</b> Use structured evaluation criteria that focus on job-relevant skills and experience. Score all candidates against the same criteria before comparing them, and avoid looking at personal details until after the initial skills assessment.</p></div></div><div class="bias-scenario" style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">Scenario 2</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;">Tom is allocating a high-profile project that could lead to promotion opportunities. He considers giving it to Emma, his top performer who always delivers excellent results. He knows Emma sometimes struggles with stakeholder management, but thinks "She is so good at everything else, I am sure she will figure it out."</p><p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px;">Is bias present in this scenario?</p><div class="scenario-options" style="display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'yes', 2)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">Yes, bias is present</button><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'no', 2)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">No bias present</button></div><div class="scenario-feedback" id="feedback-2" style="display: none; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px;"><p><b>Type of Bias:</b> Halo Effect</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Why it matters:</b> Tom is allowing Emma's strong performance in some areas to overshadow a known development need. This could set Emma up to struggle or fail, and may also mean other team members who have the right skills for this project are being overlooked.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Inclusive Leadership Action:</b> Match projects to specific skills required rather than overall "star performer" status. Consider all team members who might benefit from the opportunity, and ensure Emma receives support for her stakeholder management development regardless of the project allocation.</p></div></div><div class="bias-scenario" style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">Scenario 3</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;">During a team meeting, Priya shares an idea for improving customer response times. The conversation moves on quickly. Ten minutes later, David makes a very similar suggestion. The manager responds enthusiastically: "That is a brilliant idea, David! Let us explore that further."</p><p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px;">Is bias present in this scenario?</p><div class="scenario-options" style="display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'yes', 3)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">Yes, bias is present</button><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'no', 3)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">No bias present</button></div><div class="scenario-feedback" id="feedback-3" style="display: none; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px;"><p><b>Type of Bias:</b> Gender Bias (and potentially Confirmation Bias)</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Why it matters:</b> Priya's contribution was overlooked while an almost identical idea from David was celebrated. This pattern - sometimes called "hepeating" - disproportionately affects women and people from underrepresented groups. Over time, it discourages people from contributing and means the team loses valuable input.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Inclusive Leadership Action:</b> Actively track who is contributing ideas in meetings. When you notice a pattern of certain voices being overlooked, intervene by saying something like "I think Priya made a similar point earlier - Priya, would you like to build on that?" Create meeting norms that ensure all voices are heard.</p></div></div><div class="bias-scenario" style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">Scenario 4</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;">A new digital system is being introduced. The manager asks 25-year-old Marcus to lead the rollout, saying "You young people are so good with technology." Meanwhile, 58-year-old Helen, who has extensive project management experience and is actually very tech-savvy, is not considered for the role.</p><p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px;">Is bias present in this scenario?</p><div class="scenario-options" style="display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'yes', 4)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">Yes, bias is present</button><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'no', 4)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">No bias present</button></div><div class="scenario-feedback" id="feedback-4" style="display: none; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px;"><p><b>Type of Bias:</b> Age Bias</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Why it matters:</b> The manager made an assumption about technical ability based on age rather than actual skills. This stereotyping overlooks Helen's relevant experience and capability. It also puts pressure on Marcus to live up to an age-based assumption rather than being valued for his actual skills.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Inclusive Leadership Action:</b> When allocating opportunities, consider the specific skills required for the task and assess team members based on their demonstrated abilities, not assumptions based on age. Ask people about their interests and skills rather than assuming based on demographics.</p></div></div><div class="bias-scenario" style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">Scenario 5</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;">Chris is conducting performance reviews. Last month, team member Alex made a significant error that caused problems for a client. Chris has noticed Alex's consistent high performance over the past year, but finds himself focusing mainly on the recent mistake when writing the review. He thinks, "I always knew Alex was not as reliable as they seemed."</p><p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px;">Is bias present in this scenario?</p><div class="scenario-options" style="display: flex; gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'yes', 5)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">Yes, bias is present</button><button class="bias-answer-btn" onclick="checkBiasAnswer(this, 'no', 5)" style="padding: 12px 30px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; font-weight: 500; transition: all 0.3s;">No bias present</button></div><div class="scenario-feedback" id="feedback-5" style="display: none; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px;"><p><b>Type of Bias:</b> Confirmation Bias (combined with Recency Bias)</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Why it matters:</b> Chris is using one recent event to confirm a pre-existing doubt about Alex, while discounting a year of strong performance. This gives an unfair and inaccurate picture of Alex's contribution. It suggests Chris had already formed a negative view that he was looking to confirm.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Inclusive Leadership Action:</b> Keep regular notes on all team members' performance throughout the year, both positive and developmental. When writing reviews, systematically review the full period rather than relying on recent memory. Challenge yourself when you notice a thought like "I always knew..." - this is often a sign of confirmation bias.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>REFLECTION</h4><div><p>Now that you have worked through these scenarios, consider:</p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Were any of the biases harder to spot than others?</li><li>Have you witnessed similar situations in your own workplace?</li><li>Which inclusive leadership actions could you apply in your role?</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 15px;">In the next section, you will have the opportunity to reflect on your own potential biases before your live workshop session.</p></div></div></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
