                    <div class="section" id="dei_case_study">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>DEI CASE STUDY APPLICATION</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div style="background: #fff3cd; border: 2px solid #ffc107; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 25px;"><h4 style="color: #856404; margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 18px;">📋 Off-the-Job Evidence: DEI Case Study Application</h4><p style="color: #856404; margin: 0;">This activity provides evidence of your ability to apply DEI principles to workplace scenarios. Consider each response option carefully and think about the real-world impact of leadership decisions.</p></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>INSTRUCTIONS</h4><div><p>Read the workplace scenario below carefully. You will be presented with three possible responses that a team leader could take.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>For each response option, consider:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>How would this response affect the individuals involved?</li><li>What impact would it have on team culture?</li><li>How would it affect trust and inclusion within the team?</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 15px;">Select the response you believe is most appropriate. You will receive detailed feedback explaining the likely impact of each choice.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="interactive-activity-wrapper" id="dei-case-study"><div style="background: #f0f4ff; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 25px; border-left: 5px solid #667eea;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 15px;">THE SCENARIO: THE PROJECT PRESENTATION</h4><p style="line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;"><b>Setting:</b> <i>A busy Monday morning at a marketing agency. The team is preparing for an important client presentation later in the week.</i></p><p style="line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;">Team Leader <b>Jordan</b> is assigning roles for the upcoming client presentation. The project has been a true team effort, with everyone contributing ideas and work over the past month.</p><p style="line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;"><b>Fatima</b>, a relatively new team member who joined six months ago, developed the core creative concept that the client loved in the initial pitch. She has been working hard to refine the presentation materials and is clearly excited about the project.</p><p style="line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;"><b>Ben</b>, a long-standing team member who has been with the company for five years, is known for being confident in client meetings. He was initially skeptical of Fatima's concept but eventually supported it after the client responded positively.</p><p style="line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;">Jordan is now deciding who should lead the presentation to the client. Fatima has expressed interest in presenting her concept, but Jordan notices she seems nervous about public speaking. Ben has offered to take the lead, saying <i>"I know this client well - it just makes sense for me to do it."</i></p><p style="line-height: 1.8;"><b>Jordan must decide how to handle this situation.</b></p></div><div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;"><h4 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 20px;">How should Jordan respond?</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 20px; color: #666;">Select the response you believe is most appropriate:</p><div class="case-study-options"><button class="case-study-btn" onclick="checkCaseStudyAnswer('A')" style="display: block; width: 100%; text-align: left; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s;"><p style="margin: 0;"><b style="color: #667eea;">Option A:</b> Ask Ben to lead the presentation. He has more experience with this client and his confidence will make a better impression. Jordan can let Fatima present a smaller section to give her some exposure.</p></button><button class="case-study-btn" onclick="checkCaseStudyAnswer('B')" style="display: block; width: 100%; text-align: left; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s;"><p style="margin: 0;"><b style="color: #667eea;">Option B:</b> Have a private conversation with Fatima to understand her concerns about presenting, offer support and coaching to build her confidence, and give her the opportunity to lead the presentation of her own concept - with Ben available to support if needed.</p></button><button class="case-study-btn" onclick="checkCaseStudyAnswer('C')" style="display: block; width: 100%; text-align: left; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 2px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.3s;"><p style="margin: 0;"><b style="color: #667eea;">Option C:</b> Tell both team members that the decision will be based purely on who volunteers first for the next team meeting, making it a fair and equal process for everyone.</p></button></div><div id="case-feedback-A" style="display: none; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 20px; background: #fef3cd; border-left: 5px solid #ffc107;"><h4 style="color: #856404; margin-bottom: 15px;">Feedback: Option A - A Missed Opportunity</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;"><b>While this seems like a safe choice, it reinforces existing inequities and misses important development opportunities.</b></p><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Individuals:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Fatima</b> may feel her contribution is not valued equally, despite creating the core concept. Being given only a "smaller section" while someone else presents her work could feel demeaning and discourage future initiative.</li><li><b>Ben</b> receives another high-visibility opportunity by default, reinforcing patterns where established team members get opportunities regardless of who did the work.</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Team Culture:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li>Sends a message that seniority and confidence matter more than actual contribution</li><li>May discourage newer team members from putting forward ideas if they will not get credit</li><li>Reinforces that "safe" choices are preferred over developing talent</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Trust and Inclusion:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Trust is damaged</b> when people see that credit does not follow contribution</li><li><b>Inclusion is undermined</b> when newer or less confident team members are not given equitable opportunities to develop and shine</li><li>Creates a pattern where the same people always get visibility, regardless of merit</li></ul></div></div><div id="case-feedback-B" style="display: none; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 20px; background: #dcfce7; border-left: 5px solid #4ade80;"><h4 style="color: #166534; margin-bottom: 15px;">Feedback: Option B - Inclusive Leadership in Action ✓</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;"><b>This is the most inclusive approach. It recognises contribution, provides equitable support, and creates genuine opportunity.</b></p><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Individuals:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Fatima</b> receives recognition for her contribution and the opportunity to develop her skills with support. Her nervousness is addressed constructively rather than used as a reason to exclude her.</li><li><b>Ben</b> can still contribute meaningfully in a supporting role, and learns that opportunities are allocated based on contribution rather than seniority or self-promotion.</li><li><b>Jordan</b> demonstrates equity by providing different support based on individual needs.</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Team Culture:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li>Establishes that credit follows contribution - whoever develops the idea gets to present it</li><li>Shows that the team invests in developing all members, not just the already-confident</li><li>Encourages future innovation by demonstrating that good ideas will be recognised</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Trust and Inclusion:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Trust increases</b> when team members see fair treatment based on contribution</li><li><b>Inclusion is strengthened</b> by recognising that equity means different support for different needs - Fatima's nervousness is met with coaching, not exclusion</li><li>Newer team members see a path to visibility and growth, increasing engagement</li></ul></div></div><div id="case-feedback-C" style="display: none; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 20px; background: #fee2e2; border-left: 5px solid #f87171;"><h4 style="color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 15px;">Feedback: Option C - Equality is Not Always Equity</h4><p style="margin-bottom: 15px; line-height: 1.7;"><b>This approach confuses equality with equity. While it appears fair on the surface, it ignores the context and actually perpetuates unfairness.</b></p><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Individuals:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Fatima</b> is disadvantaged by a "neutral" process that favours those who are already confident. Her actual contribution to the project is ignored in favour of who speaks up first.</li><li><b>Ben</b> is likely to benefit from a system that rewards assertiveness over contribution, reinforcing his existing advantages.</li><li>The person who actually created the concept may not get to present it, simply due to personality differences.</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Team Culture:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li>Signals that contribution matters less than assertiveness and speed</li><li>Avoids the leader's responsibility to make fair, considered decisions</li><li>May be perceived as Jordan avoiding accountability rather than exercising good judgement</li></ul></div><div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px;"><h5 style="color: #2b3d6d; margin-bottom: 10px;">Impact on Trust and Inclusion:</h5><ul style="line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Trust erodes</b> when leaders use "fair processes" that actually produce unfair outcomes</li><li><b>Inclusion is undermined</b> because those who are naturally less assertive - often including people from underrepresented groups, introverts, or newer team members - are systematically disadvantaged</li><li>Treating everyone the same when their circumstances are different is not fairness - it is ignoring reality</li></ul></div></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="feedback-box-render"><h4>Reflection: Applying This to Your Workplace</h4><p>Now that you have considered the scenario and its impacts, think about your own workplace.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Consider these questions:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Have you witnessed situations where contribution was not matched with opportunity?</li><li>How do you currently decide who gets high-visibility opportunities in your team?</li><li>What support could you offer to help less confident team members develop?</li><li>How might you recognise and address the difference between equality and equity in your decisions?</li></ul><textarea placeholder="Write your reflection here...

Think about a specific situation where you could apply these principles. What would you do differently?"></textarea></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>KEY LEARNING POINTS</h4><div><p><b>From this case study, remember:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 15px;"><li><b>Credit should follow contribution</b> - whoever does the work should have the opportunity to present it and receive recognition</li><li><b>Equity means different support for different needs</b> - addressing nervousness with coaching is more inclusive than using it as a reason for exclusion</li><li><b>Equality is not always fair</b> - "neutral" processes can perpetuate existing inequities by favouring those who are already advantaged</li><li><b>Inclusive leaders make considered decisions</b> - they do not hide behind processes that avoid responsibility</li><li><b>Development opportunities should be distributed fairly</b> - not just given to those who are already confident or senior</li></ul></div></div></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
