                    <div class="section" id="reflection_journal">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>POST-WORK REFLECTION JOURNAL</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div style="background: #e0f2fe; border: 2px solid #0ea5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 25px;"><h4 style="color: #0369a1; margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 18px;">Portfolio Evidence: Post-Work Reflection Journal</h4><p style="color: #0369a1; margin: 0;">This reflection journal is designed to be completed <b>after your live workshop session</b>. Your reflections here can be used as evidence of off-the-job learning for your apprenticeship portfolio.</p></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>PURPOSE OF THIS REFLECTION</h4><div><p>Now that you have completed both the online pre-work and your live workshop session on <b>Inclusive Leadership in Action</b>, this journal provides an opportunity to consolidate your learning and set intentions for your ongoing development.</p><p style="margin-top: 15px;"><b>Use this space to:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Capture key insights while they are fresh in your mind</li><li>Make personal commitments to inclusive leadership behaviours</li><li>Create evidence of reflection that demonstrates your professional growth</li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div style="background: #f0fdf4; border: 1px solid #86efac; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><h4 style="color: #166534; margin-bottom: 15px;">Guidance for Writing Effective Reflections</h4><p style="color: #166534; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;">Good reflections do not need to be lengthy - they need to be <b>honest and specific</b>. Here are some tips:</p><ul style="color: #166534; line-height: 1.8;"><li><b>Be specific:</b> Rather than "I learned about bias," try "I realised I sometimes interrupt certain team members more than others"</li><li><b>Be honest:</b> This is for your own development - acknowledging areas for growth is a strength, not a weakness</li><li><b>Be actionable:</b> Connect your insights to things you can actually do differently</li><li><b>Keep it concise:</b> A few well-considered sentences are more valuable than lengthy generic statements</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="feedback-box-render"><h4>Reflection Question 1: What did I learn about my own leadership behaviours?</h4><p style="margin-top: 10px;">Think about the activities, discussions, and scenarios from both the online module and the live workshop. What stood out to you about your own approach to leadership?</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Consider:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Were there any moments of self-recognition - times when you thought "I do that"?</li><li>Did you discover any unconscious biases you were not previously aware of?</li><li>What did the inclusive vs. exclusionary leadership scenarios reveal about your own style?</li><li>How do your current behaviours compare to the inclusive leadership behaviours discussed?</li></ul><textarea placeholder="Write your reflection here...

Example: Through the bias self-assessment, I realised that I tend to give more informal development opportunities to team members who are similar to me in background. I also noticed that in the case story comparison, I recognised some of Mark's behaviours in my own approach to running meetings..."></textarea></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="feedback-box-render"><h4>Reflection Question 2: Which behaviour from the Culture Charter will I commit to role-modelling?</h4><p style="margin-top: 10px;">During your live workshop, you explored behaviours from the Culture Charter that contribute to an inclusive team environment. Choose <b>one specific behaviour</b> that you will consciously commit to demonstrating in your leadership role.</p><p style="margin-top: 10px;"><b>Consider:</b></p><ul style="margin-top: 10px;"><li>Which behaviour would have the most positive impact on your team if you consistently demonstrated it?</li><li>Which behaviour represents a stretch for you - something you can genuinely improve on?</li><li>How will you hold yourself accountable for demonstrating this behaviour?</li><li>What will "success" look like - how will you know you are making progress?</li></ul><textarea placeholder="Write your commitment here...

Example: I commit to actively seeking out and amplifying quieter voices in team meetings. Specifically, I will pause before responding to contributions and make space for others to speak. I will also proactively ask team members for their input rather than waiting for volunteers, as I recognise that some valuable perspectives are lost when I only hear from the most confident speakers..."></textarea></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div style="background: #fef3cd; border: 1px solid #ffc107; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px;"><h4 style="color: #856404; margin-bottom: 15px;">Using This as Portfolio Evidence</h4><p style="color: #856404; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;">Your completed reflection journal can serve as valuable evidence for your apprenticeship portfolio. It demonstrates:</p><ul style="color: #856404; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;"><li><b>Self-awareness:</b> The ability to honestly assess your own behaviours and identify areas for development</li><li><b>Application of learning:</b> Connecting workshop content to your real-world leadership practice</li><li><b>Commitment to growth:</b> Setting specific intentions for behavioural change</li><li><b>Professional reflection:</b> A key skill for ongoing leadership development</li></ul><p style="color: #856404; line-height: 1.8;"><b>Tip:</b> Save or print a copy of your completed reflections. You may wish to revisit them in a few weeks to assess your progress against your commitments, which would provide additional evidence of your development journey.</p></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>WHAT HAPPENS NEXT?</h4><div><p>Completing this reflection journal marks the end of your formal learning for this module. However, your journey as an inclusive leader continues:</p><ul style="margin-top: 15px;"><li><b>Put your commitment into practice</b> - start demonstrating your chosen behaviour from your next team interaction</li><li><b>Notice the impact</b> - pay attention to how your team responds when you lead inclusively</li><li><b>Seek feedback</b> - consider asking a trusted colleague or your manager for feedback on your inclusive leadership</li><li><b>Revisit your reflections</b> - return to this journal periodically to check your progress</li><li><b>Continue learning</b> - inclusive leadership is a continuous journey of growth and improvement</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 20px;"><b>Well done on completing the Inclusive Leadership in Action module!</b></p><p style="margin-top: 10px;">Your willingness to reflect honestly on your own behaviours and commit to growth is the foundation of inclusive leadership. Keep building on this foundation in your everyday leadership practice.</p></div></div></div></div></div>
